children.comment: Everything in Dart is an [Object].
children.name: Object

children.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all [Object]s is to return true if and
only if [:this:] and [other] are the same object.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override
the [hashCode] method as well to maintain consistency.
Returns a string representation of this object.
children.name: toString

children.comment:
[noSuchMethod] is invoked when users invoke a non-existant method
on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the
invocation are passed to [noSuchMethod] in an [Invocation].
If [noSuchMethod] returns a value, that value becomes the result of
the original invocation.

The default behavior of [noSuchMethod] is to throw a
[noSuchMethodError].
children.name: noSuchMethod

children.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the
same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality
operator [:==:]. Other than that there are no guarantees about
the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and
there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides [hashCode] it should override the
equality operator as well to maintain consistency.
children.name: hashCode

children.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.
children.name: runtimeType

children.comment:
Creates a new [Object] instance.

[Object] instances have no meaningful state, and are only useful
through their identity. An [Object] instance is equal to itself
only.
children.name: Object

children.comment:
A marker interface implemented by all core library exceptions.

An [Exception] is intended to convey information to the user about a failure,
so that the error can be addressed programmatically. It is intended to be
caught, and it should contain useful data fields.

Creating instances of [Exception] directly with [:new Exception("message"):]
is discouraged, and only included as a temporary measure during development,
until the actual exceptions used by a library are done.
children.name: Exception

children.comment:
Returns a [ClassMirror] for the class represented by a Dart
Type object.

This only works with objects local to the current isolate.
children.name: reflectClass

children.comment:
Returns an [InstanceMirror] for some Dart language object.

This only works if this mirror system is associated with the
current running isolate.
children.name: reflect

children.comment:
Creates a [MirrorSystem] for the isolate which is listening on
the [SendPort].
children.name: mirrorSystemOf

children.comment: Returns a [MirrorSystem] for the current isolate.
children.name: currentMirrorSystem

children.comment: Class used for encoding comments as metadata annotations.
children.name: Comment

children.comment: The comment text as written in the source text.
children.name: text

children.comment:
The comment text without the start, end, and padding text.

For example, if [text] is [: /** Comment text. */ :] then the [trimmedText]
is [: Comment text. :].
children.name: trimmedText

children.comment:
Is [:true:] if this comment is a documentation comment.

That is, that the comment is either enclosed in [: /** ... */ :] or starts
with [: /// :].
children.name: isDocComment

children.comment:
A [MirrorException] is used to indicate errors within the mirrors
framework.
children.name: MirrorException

children.comment:
When a compile-time error occurs during the mirrored execution
of code, a [MirroredCompilationError] is thrown.

This exception includes the compile-time error message that would
have been displayed to the user, if the function had not been
invoked via mirror.
children.name: MirroredCompilationError

children.comment:
When an uncaught exception occurs during the mirrored execution
of code, a [MirroredUncaughtExceptionError] is thrown.

This exception contains a mirror on the original exception object.
It also contains an object which can be used to recover the
stacktrace.
children.name: MirroredUncaughtExceptionError

children.comment: A mirror on the exception object.
children.name: exception_mirror

children.comment: The result of toString() for the exception object.
children.name: exception_string

children.comment: A stacktrace object for the uncaught exception.
children.name: stacktrace

children.comment:
When an error occurs during the mirrored execution of code, a
[MirroredError] is thrown.

In general, there are three main classes of failure that can happen
during mirrored execution of code in some isolate:

- An exception is thrown but not caught.  This is caught by the
  mirrors framework and a [MirroredUncaughtExceptionError] is
  created and thrown.

- A compile-time error occurs, such as a syntax error.  This is
  suppressed by the mirrors framework and a
  [MirroredCompilationError] is created and thrown.

- A truly fatal error occurs, causing the isolate to be exited.  If
  the reflector and reflectee share the same isolate, then they
  will both suffer.  If the reflector and reflectee are in distinct
  isolates, then we hope to provide some information about the
  isolate death, but this has yet to be implemented.

TODO(turnidge): Specify the behavior for remote fatal errors.
children.name: MirroredError

children.comment: A [SourceLocation] describes the span of an entity in Dart source code.
children.name: SourceLocation

children.comment: A [ParameterMirror] reflects a Dart formal parameter declaration.
children.name: ParameterMirror

children.comment: A mirror on the type of this parameter.
children.name: type

children.comment: Is this parameter optional?
children.name: isOptional

children.comment: Is this parameter named?
children.name: isNamed

children.comment: Does this parameter have a default value?
children.name: hasDefaultValue

children.comment: A mirror on the default value for this parameter, if it exists.
children.name: defaultValue

children.comment: A [VariableMirror] reflects a Dart language variable declaration.
children.name: VariableMirror

children.comment: A mirror on the type of the reflectee.
children.name: type

children.comment:
Is the reflectee a static variable?

For the purposes of the mirror library, top-level variables are
implicitly declared static.
children.name: isStatic

children.comment: Is the reflectee a final variable?
children.name: isFinal

children.comment:
A [MethodMirror] reflects a Dart language function, method,
constructor, getter, or setter.
children.name: MethodMirror

children.comment: A mirror on the return type for the reflectee.
children.name: returnType

children.comment: A list of mirrors on the parameters for the reflectee.
children.name: parameters

children.comment:
Is the reflectee static?

For the purposes of the mirrors library, a top-level function is
considered static.
children.name: isStatic

children.comment: Is the reflectee abstract?
children.name: isAbstract

children.comment:
Is the reflectee a regular function or method?

A function or method is regular if it is not a getter, setter, or
constructor.  Note that operators, by this definition, are
regular methods.
children.name: isRegularMethod

children.comment: Is the reflectee an operator?
children.name: isOperator

children.comment: Is the reflectee a getter?
children.name: isGetter

children.comment: Is the reflectee a setter?
children.name: isSetter

children.comment: Is the reflectee a constructor?
children.name: isConstructor

children.comment:
The constructor name for named constructors and factory methods.

For unnamed constructors, this is the empty string.  For
non-constructors, this is the empty string.

For example, [:'bar':] is the constructor name for constructor
[:Foo.bar:] of type [:Foo:].
children.name: constructorName

children.comment: Is the reflectee a const constructor?
children.name: isConstConstructor

children.comment: Is the reflectee a generative constructor?
children.name: isGenerativeConstructor

children.comment: Is the reflectee a redirecting constructor?
children.name: isRedirectingConstructor

children.comment: Is the reflectee a factory constructor?
children.name: isFactoryConstructor

children.comment: A [TypedefMirror] represents a typedef in a Dart language program.
children.name: TypedefMirror

children.comment:
The defining type for this typedef.

For instance [:void f(int):] is the value for [:typedef void f(int):].
children.name: value

children.comment:
A [TypeVariableMirror] represents a type parameter of a generic
type.
children.name: TypeVariableMirror

children.comment: A mirror on the type that is the upper bound of this type variable.
children.name: upperBound

children.comment:
A [FunctionTypeMirror] represents the type of a function in the
Dart language.
children.name: FunctionTypeMirror

children.comment: The return type of the reflectee.
children.name: returnType

children.comment: A list of the parameter types of the reflectee.
children.name: parameters

children.comment:
A mirror on the [:call:] method for the reflectee.

TODO(turnidge): What is this and what is it for?
children.name: callMethod

children.comment: A [ClassMirror] reflects a Dart language class.
children.name: ClassMirror

children.comment:
Invokes the named constructor and returns a mirror on the result.
The arguments are objects local to the current isolate
children.name: newInstance

children.comment:
Invokes the named constructor and returns a mirror on the result.
The arguments must be instances of [InstanceMirror], [num],
[String] or [bool].
children.name: newInstanceAsync

children.comment:
A mirror on the superclass on the reflectee.

If this type is [:Object:] or a typedef, the superClass will be
null.
children.name: superclass

children.comment: A list of mirrors on the superinterfaces of the reflectee.
children.name: superinterfaces

children.comment:
An immutable map from from names to mirrors for all members of
this type.

The members of a type are its methods, fields, getters, and
setters.  Note that constructors and type variables are not
considered to be members of a type.

This does not include inherited members.
children.name: members

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all method,
declarations for this type.  This does not include getters and
setters.
children.name: methods

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all getter
declarations for this type.
children.name: getters

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all setter
declarations for this type.
children.name: setters

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all variable
declarations for this type.
children.name: variables

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all constructor
declarations for this type.
children.name: constructors

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all type variables for
this type.

This map preserves the order of declaration of the type variables.
children.name: typeVariables

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all type arguments for
this type.

This map preserves the order of declaration of the type variables.
children.name: typeArguments

children.comment:
Is this the original declaration of this type?

For most classes, they are their own original declaration.  For
generic classes, however, there is a distinction between the
original class declaration, which has unbound type variables, and
the instantiations of generic classes, which have bound type
variables.
children.name: isOriginalDeclaration

children.comment:
A mirror on the original declaration of this type.

For most classes, they are their own original declaration.  For
generic classes, however, there is a distinction between the
original class declaration, which has unbound type variables, and
the instantiations of generic classes, which have bound type
variables.
children.name: originalDeclaration

children.comment:
Does this mirror represent a class?

TODO(turnidge): This functions goes away after the
class/interface changes.
children.name: isClass

children.comment:
A mirror on the default factory class or null if there is none.

TODO(turnidge): This functions goes away after the
class/interface changes.
children.name: defaultFactory

children.comment:
A [TypeMirror] reflects a Dart language class, typedef,
or type variable.
children.name: TypeMirror

children.comment:
A [LibraryMirror] reflects a Dart language library, providing
access to the variables, functions, and classes of the
library.
children.name: LibraryMirror

children.comment: The absolute uri of the library.
children.name: uri

children.comment:
An immutable map from from names to mirrors for all members in
this library.

The members of a library are its top-level classes,
functions, variables, getters, and setters.
children.name: members

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all class
declarations in this library.
children.name: classes

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all function, getter,
and setter declarations in this library.
children.name: functions

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all getter
declarations in this library.
children.name: getters

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all setter
declarations in this library.
children.name: setters

children.comment:
An immutable map from names to mirrors for all variable
declarations in this library.
children.name: variables

children.comment:
A [ClosureMirror] reflects a closure.

A [ClosureMirror] provides access to its captured variables and
provides the ability to execute its reflectee.
children.name: ClosureMirror

children.comment:
Executes the closure.
The arguments are objects local to the current isolate.
children.name: apply

children.comment:
Executes the closure.
The arguments must be instances of [InstanceMirror], [num],
[String], or [bool].
children.name: applyAsync

children.comment:
Looks up the value of a name in the scope of the closure. The
result is a mirror on that value.
children.name: findInContext

children.comment: A mirror on the function associated with this closure.
children.name: function

children.comment:
The source code for this closure, if available.  Otherwise null.

TODO(turnidge): Would this just be available in function?
children.name: source

children.comment: An [InstanceMirror] reflects an instance of a Dart language object.
children.name: InstanceMirror

children.comment:
Perform [invocation] on [reflectee].

If [reflectee] doesn't support the invocation, its [noSuchMethod]
method will be called with either [invocation] or another
equivalent instance of [Invocation].
children.name: delegate

children.comment: A mirror on the type of the reflectee.
children.name: type

children.comment:
Does [reflectee] contain the instance reflected by this mirror?
This will always be true in the local case (reflecting instances
in the same isolate), but only true in the remote case if this
mirror reflects a simple value.

A value is simple if one of the following holds:
 - the value is null
 - the value is of type [num]
 - the value is of type [bool]
 - the value is of type [String]
children.name: hasReflectee

children.comment:
If the [InstanceMirror] reflects an instance it is meaningful to
have a local reference to, we provide access to the actual
instance here.

If you access [reflectee] when [hasReflectee] is false, an
exception is thrown.
children.name: reflectee

children.comment:
An [ObjectMirror] is a common superinterface of [InstanceMirror],
[ClassMirror], and [LibraryMirror] that represents their shared
functionality.

For the purposes of the mirrors library, these types are all
object-like, in that they support method invocation and field
access.  Real Dart objects are represented by the [InstanceMirror]
type.

See [InstanceMirror], [ClassMirror], and [LibraryMirror].
children.name: ObjectMirror

children.comment:
Invokes the named function and returns a mirror on the result.
The arguments are objects local to the current isolate.
children.name: invoke

children.comment:
Invokes a getter and returns a mirror on the result. The getter
can be the implicit getter for a field or a user-defined getter
method.
children.name: getField

children.comment:
Invokes a setter and returns a mirror on the result. The setter
may be either the implicit setter for a non-final field or a
user-defined setter method.
The argument is an object local to the current isolate.
children.name: setField

children.comment:
Invokes the named function and returns a mirror on the result.
The arguments must be instances of [InstanceMirror], [num],
[String], or [bool].
children.name: invokeAsync

children.comment:
Invokes a getter and returns a mirror on the result. The getter
can be the implicit getter for a field or a user-defined getter
method.
children.name: getFieldAsync

children.comment:
Invokes a setter and returns a mirror on the result. The setter
may be either the implicit setter for a non-final field or a
user-defined setter method.
The argument must be an instance of either [InstanceMirror], [num],
[String], or [bool].
children.name: setFieldAsync

children.comment: A [DeclarationMirror] reflects some entity declared in a Dart program.
children.name: DeclarationMirror

children.comment:
The simple name for this Dart language entity.

The simple name is in most cases the the identifier name of the
entity, such as 'method' for a method [:void method() {...}:] or
'mylibrary' for a [:#library('mylibrary');:] declaration.
children.name: simpleName

children.comment:
The fully-qualified name for this Dart language entity.

This name is qualified by the name of the owner. For instance,
the qualified name of a method 'method' in class 'Class' in
library 'library' is 'library.Class.method'.

TODO(turnidge): Specify whether this name is unique.  Currently
this is a gray area due to lack of clarity over whether library
names are unique.
children.name: qualifiedName

children.comment:
A mirror on the owner of this function.  This is the declaration
immediately surrounding the reflectee.

Note that for libraries, the owner will be [:null:].
children.name: owner

children.comment:
Is this declaration private?

Note that for libraries, this will be [:false:].
children.name: isPrivate

children.comment:
Is this declaration top-level?

This is defined to be equivalent to:
   [:mirror.owner != null && mirror.owner is LibraryMirror:]
children.name: isTopLevel

children.comment: The source location of this Dart language entity.
children.name: location

children.comment: An [IsolateMirror] reflects an isolate.
children.name: IsolateMirror

children.comment: A unique name used to refer to an isolate in debugging messages.
children.name: debugName

children.comment: Does this mirror reflect the currently running isolate?
children.name: isCurrent

children.comment: A mirror on the root library for this isolate.
children.name: rootLibrary

children.comment:
A [Mirror] reflects some Dart language entity.

Every [Mirror] originates from some [MirrorSystem].
children.name: Mirror

children.comment: The [MirrorSystem] that contains this mirror.
children.name: mirrors

children.comment:
A [MirrorSystem] is the main interface used to reflect on a set of
associated libraries.

At runtime each running isolate has a distinct [MirrorSystem].

It is also possible to have a [MirrorSystem] which represents a set
of libraries which are not running -- perhaps at compile-time.  In
this case, all available reflective functionality would be
supported, but runtime functionality (such as invoking a function
or inspecting the contents of a variable) would fail dynamically.
children.name: MirrorSystem

children.comment:
Returns an iterable of all libraries in the mirror system whose library
name is [libraryName].
children.name: findLibrary

children.comment:
An immutable map from from library names to mirrors for all
libraries known to this mirror system.
children.name: libraries

children.comment:
A mirror on the isolate associated with this [MirrorSystem].
This may be null if this mirror system is not running.
children.name: isolate

children.comment: A mirror on the [:dynamic:] type.
children.name: dynamicType

children.comment: A mirror on the [:void:] type.
children.name: voidType
